Getting Started
Introduction
The Blackout Rugby API (Application Programming Interface) uses the RESTful architecture to provide game information such as team data, player data, and fixture data to 3rd party software applications. Developers can also update and manipulate game data via the API. Anyone can gain access to the API, and use it to develop any type of 3rd party software application. If you're not a developer, you can stop reading now.
Getting Access
To get started with the API, you need to activate your developer account. Go to your Account page, and click "Activate API Developer Account".

Once you’ve got a developer ID (also found on your Account page), you can start making requests. Requests are made by sending a GET query to the API, which will respond in XML.

Developer's also have access to the API Developer's lounge in the clubrooms. We encourage you to join this lounge to stay up to date with the latest changes. This is where you should request features, report bugs, etc.

The default base URL for requests is:
http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com

You can make requests from your browser to test the API and view XML responses. We recommend Firefox for this.

You can also make use of SSL:
https://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com

We recommend using SSL when sending write data to the API, especially with log-ins and any other sensitive requests.

All requests are handled by our load balancer with auto-scaling capacity, and will make use of caching where possible. However, we ask that you also use caching in your own applications to minimise the load on our servers and to keep the API speedy for everyone using it as well as the people using our web site.
Your First Request
Copy and paste the following URL to the address bar in a new browser window/tab:
http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com/?d=[DEV_ID]&dk=[DEV_KEY]
&r=m&memberid=[MEMBER_ID]


Replace the bracketed sections with the required developer information from your account page, and grab your member ID from your member lobby.

Replace everything in the bracketed text, including the brackets. So your final URL should look something like this:
http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com/?d=0&dk=abcdefghijk
&r=m&memberid=0


Load the URL, and you've just made your first request! You should see the XML data representing your public account information. If you go on to add your member key (also found on the account page), you will see some extra private information as well.
JSON (New)
Due to JSON's ease of use and relatively smaller response size (therefore faster performance), it is being rolled out in all new APIs and will eventually be added to all current APIs as well.

By default all APIs will respond in XML, but if you add the following to your request to a supporting API it will respond in JSON:
&json=1


In a future version of the API, JSON will become the default, requiring XML to be specified if needed.

All JSON responses will contain an item called "status", this can be tested for "Ok" representing a successful response, or "Failed" for an error. Here's an example of an error:
{
	status: "Failed",
	error: "Player is not for sale",
	brt: "2013-11-13T22:09:31+12:00"
}


"brt" is Blackout Rugby Time formatted to ISO 8601.

Continuing on from "Your First Request", try the following request to see what a full JSON response looks like (Best viewed with a JSON viewer installed in your browser, such as JSONView):
http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com/?d=[DEV_ID]&dk=[DEV_KEY]
&r=m&memberid=[MEMBER_ID]&json=1
Requesting with JSON (New)
As we expand the API to accept requests which actually change things in the game, there is a need for more flexibility.

For example, sending in a group of training instructions would be much better suited to something like arrays, which are able to describe data in a multidimensional way as opposed the basic http requests which are limited to a single list.

This is where JSON really starts to shine, with it's ability to hold and transport multi-dimensional data quite easily.

Due to this, the API now supports the ability to make requests in JSON for all current APIs.

Simply construct your request as a JSON object, with the same keys and values normally sent to the API via GET and POST, and send it to the server as a single POST key named "json".

For example, you would construct your JSON request as an array in your language of choice. Here's an example in PHP:
$request = array(
	"d" => "[DEV_ID]",
	"dk" => "[DEV_KEY]",
	"r" => "m",
	"memberid" => [MEMBER_ID]
);


Then you would encode the request as JSON:
$request = json_encode($request);

This function, json_encode is provided by default in PHP. There should be something similar in most languages.

This results in a JSON object like this:
{
	d: "[DEV_ID]",
	dk: "[DEV_KEY]",
	r: "m",
	memberid: [MEMBER_ID]
}


As a flat string:
{"d":"[DEV_ID]","dk":"[DEV_KEY]","r":"m","memberid":[MEMBER_ID]}


Encode this string for sending over HTTP:
$request = urlencode($request);

Again, urlencode is built into PHP. Most languages will come with functions or libraries bundled in for handling this.

Then you simply send this as either GET or POST to the API under the "json" key:
http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com/?json=%7B%22d%22%...


Important: This JSON data should preferably by sent using POST since this handles large amounts of data. Whereas sending within the URL (as above) will limit you to 2000 characters.

For information on sending encrypted data within this JSON request, see the JSON section under "Security".
Debugging
To tell the API to return back to you exactly what it's seeing, including any unencrypted strings, you can add the following flag to your request (it doesn't matter where... URI, POST, JSON):
debug=1


This will come in very handy when testing your setup.
Versioning
The API provides a latest version as well as well as several previous versions based on the date they were saved.

To use the latest version of the API, use the normal base URL:

api.blackoutrugby.com/...


To use a previous version of the API, use a URL like this:

api.blackoutrugby.com/2011-08-13/...


You can find the available versions by checking the different API reference dates provided in the documentation below.

Why use a versioned API?
To prevent changes in the API from breaking your application, you should use a specific version of the API. Then when you want to upgrade to a newer version, you can test your app with other versions whenever you're ready.

Please note we do not plan on keeping all versions forever. We will warn you at least 21 days in advance via the developer's lounge before removing old versions of the API.
Charges
Access to the API is free. The only scenarios in which we would charge for API access is if the developer was charging for their product, or if usage became so high that we had to charge users to offset our hosting costs.

If a developer decides to make a commercial product using our API, we would come to a mutually beneficial deal for both parties and charge the developer directly.

If we were to charge for high usage to offset hosting costs, we would charge users directly from within Blackout Rugby via a low price "API subscription". However, we do not envisage this happening for a very long time, if ever.
Official Third Party Applications
If you want your application to become an official Blackout Rugby third party application. Please send us a request to support@blackoutrugby.com. This should include any information required so that we can review your application. We reserve the right to also request your source code.

If you are accepted, you should use the following image somewhere on your site/application. You can resize it to whatever size you need:
http://www.blackoutrugby.com/resources/official.third.party.ap...
Bulk Downloads/Updates
The API is designed to handle smaller distributed requests over time rather than bulk downloads. This allows the system to scale gracefully when traffic increases. Bulk downloads cause spikes in traffic, and can have negative impacts on the overall service. When designing your application, please keep this in mind.

The most ideal use of the API when running lengthy scripts is as follows:

1. During 0-120 seconds, wait 3 seconds between requests
2. 120-240 seconds, wait 1 second between requests
3. After than you can run each request without waiting.

This prevents the system from getting overwhelmed too quickly, allowing it to scale gracefully - especially during low peak when we have minimal servers running. If possible, please only run intensive scripts during peak hours when we have plenty of servers running. This is between 12am and 10am Blackout Rugby Time (BRT).

Please do not run concurrent requests.
Security
Developer ID
To receive an informational response from the API, you must always provide your developer ID and Key for example:
http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com/?d=[DEVELOPER_ID]&dk=[DEVELOPER_KEY]


This is all that is needed to to get an informational response from the API while testing (from a browser for example). However, you should never use this method from within an application, otherwise you risk exposing your developer key to someone who uses your application, especially if it is a desktop application or browser extension.

You must protect your developer key at all times.

From within your application, you must encrypt the actual request string in a closed source application before sending it to the API.
Encrypted Requests
In addition to your developer ID, you are provided with a developer key, and an IV (Initialisation Vector). These are used with AES encryption to encrypt your request string.

So how do you use AES? First of all, let’s jump straight to the final product, and then work towards it. The GET requests from your application to the API should look something like this:
http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com/?d=[DEV_ID]&er=[ENCRYPTED_REQUEST]


and if you're adding POST data as well, you would still call the URL above including "er=", and you would also provide an encrypted request string as your POST data:

&er=[ENCRYPTED_POST_DATA]


You use the same techniques to encrypt your POST data, as you do for your GET data.

To generate the encrypted request string, you first create your string which is simple enough, e.g. “r=p&playerid=[PLAYER_ID]” (see the API reference). Once you have created your request string. You encrypt it using AES in CBC mode with zero padding, and finally you encode it to base64. We encode to base64 so that the string can be safely sent over HTTP.

This task will obviously be different depending on which programming language you’re using. Regardless of which language you use, you must ensure you use “Zero” padding (Bytes set to 0). AES requires the byte length of your unencrypted string to be a multiple of 8, so if the length of your string in terms of bytes is not exactly a multiple of 8, e.g. 16, 24, or 32 characters long (which it rarely will be), your AES library will pad your string to make it big enough. This task is usually done by the AES library or object which you use, all you have to do is specify the type of padding. However, if your library or object does not do this for you, it is fairly easy to code.

Please see the AES Sample Code section for some sample code for several popular programming languages.
Encrypting JSON
When sending encrypted requests via JSON, you should:

1. create your JSON request object as shown in the Getting Started section called "Requesting with JSON".
2. Encrypt this string just as it is, without adding a "json=" key or anything like that. Just encrypt the raw JSON string.
3. Place that encrypted string within another JSON object, coupled with your developer ID:
{
	"er":"6FJQWybNd61Qt+PRz+9uQcuLDsBhJ9==",
	"d":1
}


4. Encode (for URLs) and send this JSON object as normal, preferably via POST:
POST: json=%7B%22d%22%...
Member ID
Using a developer ID alone, you can gain access to public information such as fixtures and public player data. However, to access sensitive information such as player skills, you will need to provide a member ID and a member key.

The member ID and member key are provided on every member’s “My Account” page on the Blackout Rugby website, in a format ready to be added to any request URL. You will need to ask your users to copy and paste their access key into your application. We ask that if you are storing these keys in a central location (for a web application as opposed to on a user’s PC for a desktop application), that you take the proper precautions to protect these keys.

The key provided to users looks like
m=[MEMBER_ID]&mk=[MEMBER_KEY]


This should normally be encrypted as part of the encrypted request string, but it can also be added straight onto the base URL with a developer ID and key when testing, for example:
...rugby.com/?d=[DEV_ID]&dk=[DEV_KEY]&m=[MEMBER_ID]&mk=[MEMBER_KEY]


The member access key is based on the user’s password. So if the user changes their password, they will need to re-enter their access key into your application.
Writes
Write Access
Most APIs that allow you to manipulate data are now available to all API developers. However, certain APIs such as registration require special access. For now, we are only allowing official Blackout Rugby applications developed by us or internal staff members to access these. If you really need these features, you should contact us at theteam@blackoutrugby.com.
Writing to the API
A write to the API is a request which updates data in some way, such as updating a lineup, sending in-game mail, or setting some training. All writes to the API require a POST request to be made.

When writing to the API, you should send your POST request to a URL which includes only the developer ID:
http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com/?d=[DEVELOPER_ID]


All other data (including your developer key) should be encrypted, and sent with the POST data:
POST
er=[ENCRYPTED_REQUEST]


When testing, you can send unencrypted values via POST:
POST
dk=[DEVELOPER_KEY]&r=[REQUEST_TYPE]&...
AES Sample Code
PHP
C#
using System;
using System.Security.Cryptography;
using System.Text;
using System.IO;

// Create an unencrypted request as an array of bytes
byte[] request = UTF8Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes("[REQUEST_STRING]");

// Set the dev ID
string devID = "[DEVELOPER_ID]";

// Set the key and IV as arrays of bytes
byte[] key = UTF8Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes("[DEVELOPER_KEY]");
byte[] iv = UTF8Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes("[DEVELOPER]");

// Create an instance of the AES Encryptor
AesCryptoServiceProvider aes = new AesCryptoServiceProvider();

// Set the key and IV
aes.Key = key;
aes.IV = iv;

// Set the mode of the AES Encryptor
aes.Mode = CipherMode.CBC;

// Set the padding mode of the AES Encryptor
aes.Padding = PaddingMode.Zeros;

// Get the transformer from the AES Encryptor
ICryptoTransform cTransform = aes.CreateEncryptor();

// Use the transformer to encrypt our request
byte[] result = 
  cTransform.TransformFinalBlock(request, 0, request.Length);

// Release resources held by AES Encryptor
aes.Clear();

// Encode to base64
string encryptedRequest = 
  Convert.ToBase64String(result, 0, result.Length);

// Send request to API
string baseURL = "http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com/";
string requestString = "?d="+devID+"&er="+encryptedRequest;
string response = getWebResponse(baseURL+requestString);

// NOTE: getWebResponse() is a fictitious method
// You will need to write your own code for web requests
