Error Handling
Error Handling
When developing your application, you will need to ensure your application can handle any errors. All errors are provided in a standard element in XML, or an error child in JSON with the status "Failed". If you request the base URL with no arguments: http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com you will receive the error: “Developer ID is not set”.

An example of good error handling is to tell the user if their credentials are incorrect. If you make the following request to the API:
http://classic-api.blackoutrugby.com/?d=[DEV_ID]&m=[MEMBER_ID]&mk=[MEMBER_KEY]

And if the user’s credentials are correct, you will receive the error message “No data requested”, so you can tell the user that their credentials are successful. However, if the user’s credentials are incorrect, you will receive the error message “Member key is incorrect”, and your application should tell the user to try again.

There are many error messages which you will likely encounter, and we will not provide every error message here in the documentation. You should simply attempt error provoking scenarios when testing, and ensure your application does not break when encountering an error.
Error Reporting
API based error messages will not have a location and line attached, however, PHP based errors will. So if you see an error message including the code location information, please let us know via the bugs lounge so that we can fix it.
